                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p32n5040v/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>hold back from active service. May I presume to in-<lb/>dulge some\n                                        friendly advice, similar to that which<lb/> you reprovingly\n                                                  <sic>admiministered</sic> to me some years<lb/>\n                                        ago, when I was about withdrawing from the ministry?<lb/> It\n                                        is true, you have not altogether withdrawn from the<lb/>\n                                        legitimate labors of your vacation. You are en-<lb/>gaged in\n                                        literary undertakings, which will prove<lb/> of great\n                                        benefit to our people. But in my humble<lb/>\n                                        <sic>judgement</sic>, these need not be abandoned, tho'\n                                        their ex-<lb/>ecution might be attended with some\n                                        difficulty, were<lb/> you to accept office in this city. I\n                                        would therefore<lb/> say, weigh the matter well, before you\n                                        come to a<lb/> final determination; and altho' the terms,\n                                        under which<lb/> the office is offered to you, may at first\n                                        sight app-<lb/>ear humiliating to your pride in a worldly\n                                        point<lb/> of view, yet I cannot conceive, how it can\n                                        affect<lb/> your well established character. The reduction\n                                        of<lb/> salary only tends to show the straitened means\n                                        of<lb/> the congregation, but cannot in any shape or\n                                        manner<lb/> be tortured to argue the inferiority of the\n                                        successor<lb/> to the present incumbent. The very attempt to\n                                        do so<lb/> would be ridiculous. Any one might with the\n                                        same<lb/> propriety contend, that I am totally unfit for\n                                        the<lb/> office, because I receive less than half the\n                                        sal-<lb/>ary of my worthy colleague. Were the Salary<lb/>\n                                        therefore the only consideration, you have no right<lb/> to\n                                        decline. Regarding, however, the prospect of</p>"
                  },
