              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p32n5040v/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>election and term of office I can say but little.<lb/> In this\n                                        respect you must be guided by your own<lb/> feelings.\n                                        Nothing, however, I assume you would give<lb/> me greater\n                                        pleasure than to see you again at the<lb/> head of a\n                                        respectable congregation, and more part-<lb/>icularly in my\n                                        immediate neighborhood.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I am greatly indebted to you<lb/> for the prompt\n                                        manner, in which you came forth<lb/> in <sic>defence</sic>\n                                        of my name in the Occident. I <sic>dont</sic><lb/> think,\n                                        however, that <persName>Mr. Mack</persName> did not mean\n                                        to<lb/> depreciate my character. He is an inexperienced<lb/>\n                                        writer and no doubt hits upon the words for the<lb/>\n                                        rounding of the sentence. You must know, that<lb/>\n                                        <persName>Mr Mack</persName> was one of my staunchest\n                                        supporters<lb/> who would have made a pretty little\n                                        sacrifice, could<lb/> he have secured my reelection in\n                                                  <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>.<lb/> And well\n                                        he might. No one knows better than <persName>Mr<lb/>\n                                                  M.</persName> thro' what labor I have gone in\n                                        behalf of his synagogue and congregation, how strenuous and\n                                        per-<lb/>severing were my exertions in promoting its\n                                        welfare<lb/> and establishing its character for the paltry\n                                        sum<lb/> of $500 p. a. he is the last of all men, whom<lb/>\n                                        I could have thought capable of casting a reflect<lb/>ion on\n                                        my efficiency. The very school, of which he<lb/> boasts so\n                                        much, was called into life chiefly<lb/> thro' my\n                                        cooperation. And I had intended to send<lb/> you a sermon,\n                                        which I delivered 4 years ago</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p32n5040v/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
            }
